    {
        "user": "UGWUJUZHT",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1776086032.482019",
        "client_msg_id": "aa2c85ba-2e6d-4152-adfb-b608ba5acdb7",
        "text": "Yes!\n\nActually, I find that I want a more precise syntax than English and tend to give up using LLM’s to generate code (that I care about) for me, especially when I’m going off of the beaten path where a no-code approach (e.g. LLMs) can’t be very helpful. I typically end up giving up on conversing with an LLM after about 3 tries. Currently my go-to tool is OhmJS plus Ohm-editor(_brilliant_) plus a little thingie I call RWR (I call the whole package ‘T2T’).\n\n&gt; Are these DSLs?\nMy observation is that the word “DSL” has been misappropriated to mean something heavy-weight like a 20th century compiler. I’ve been using the term SCN (Solution Centric Notation), although I will keep your term PSL in the back of mind. I even have an allergy to the term “language” because it seems to automatically generate visions of text-only syntax. We can do better today. I routinely parse and compile 2D diagrams to running code… (I guess I was trying to quietly show how I do this in the above article\/repo (along with some other articles\/youtubes)) (<@U01ULEWACPP>)",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "41a8bada7812",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2023-02-06\/4754627914258_41a8bada781281751d07_72.jpg",
            "first_name": "",
            "real_name": "Paul Tarvydas",
            "display_name": "guitarvydas",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "paultarvydas",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1775653615.497359",
        "parent_user_id": "UGWUJUZHT",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "JlqaB",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Yes!\n\nActually, I find that I want a more precise syntax than English and tend to give up using LLM’s to generate code (that I care about) for me, especially when I’m going off of the beaten path where a no-code approach (e.g. LLMs) can’t be very helpful. I typically end up giving up on conversing with an LLM after about 3 tries. Currently my go-to tool is OhmJS plus Ohm-editor("
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "brilliant",
                                "style": {
                                    "italic": true
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": ") plus a little thingie I call RWR (I call the whole package ‘T2T’).\n\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_quote",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Are these DSLs?"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\nMy observation is that the word “DSL” has been misappropriated to mean something heavy-weight like a 20th century compiler. I’ve been using the term SCN (Solution Centric Notation), although I will keep your term PSL in the back of mind. I even have an allergy to the term “language” because it seems to automatically generate visions of text-only syntax. We can do better today. I routinely parse and compile 2D diagrams to running code… (I guess I was trying to quietly show how I do this in the above article\/repo (along with some other articles\/youtubes)) ("
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "user",
                                "user_id": "U01ULEWACPP"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": ")"
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
